Background & Context¶

The Thera bank recently saw a steep decline in the number of users of their credit card, credit cards are a good source of income for banks because of different kinds of fees charged by the banks like annual fees, balance transfer fees, and cash advance fees, late payment fees, foreign transaction fees, and others. Some fees are charged to every user irrespective of usage, while others are charged under specified circumstances.

Customers’ leaving credit cards services would lead bank to loss, so the bank wants to analyze the data of customers and identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and reason for same – so that bank could improve upon those areas

You as a Data scientist at Thera bank need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

You need to identify the best possible model that will give the required performance

Objective¶

Explore and visualize the dataset. Build a classification model to predict if the customer is going to churn or not Optimize the model using appropriate techniques Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the bank

Data Dictionary:¶

CLIENTNUM: Client number. Unique identifier for the customer holding the account

Attrition_Flag: Internal event (customer activity) variable - if the account is closed then "Attrited Customer" else "Existing Customer"

Customer_Age: Age in Years

Gender: Gender of the account holder

Dependent_count: Number of dependents

Education_Level: Educational Qualification of the account holder - Graduate, High School, Unknown, Uneducated, College(refers to a college student), Post-Graduate, Doctorate.

Marital_Status: Marital Status of the account holder

Income_Category: Annual Income Category of the account holder

Card_Category: Type of Card

Months_on_book: Period of relationship with the bank

Total_Relationship_Count: Total no. of products held by the customer

Months_Inactive_12_mon: No. of months inactive in the last 12 months

Contacts_Count_12_mon: No. of Contacts between the customer and bank in the last 12 months

Credit_Limit: Credit Limit on the Credit Card

Total_Revolving_Bal: The balance that carries over from one month to the next is the revolving balance

Avg_Open_To_Buy: Open to Buy refers to the amount left on the credit card to use (Average of last 12 months)

Total_Trans_Amt: Total Transaction Amount (Last 12 months)

Total_Trans_Ct: Total Transaction Count (Last 12 months)

Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1: Ratio of the total transaction count in 4th quarter and the total transaction count in 1st quarter

Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1: Ratio of the total transaction amount in 4th quarter and the total transaction amount in 1st quarter

Avg_Utilization_Ratio: Represents how much of the available credit the customer spent

Univariate EDA - Numerical Columns¶

In [244]:
df[numerical_cols].hist(figsize=(14, 14))
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Customer age seems to have a Gaussian distribution
  • Most customers seem to have dependents, which makes sense since age profile of customers is in the older range
  • Months on book has a high peak at around 36-38 months, which is interesting since all the other bins are less than half in proportion
  • Most customers hold more than 1 product from the bank
  • Most customers have 1-3 inactive months in the past 12 months.
  • Most customers have had 2-3 contacts with the bank in the past 12 months.
  • Credit Limit and Average open to buy are right-skewed, similar to Avg utilization ratio, which is also right skewed, there is a sharp peak between 0 and 0.10, which means that a lot of customers spend and remain within 10\% of their credit limit.
  • There is a peak of total revolving balance of \$0, since there are always customers who pay off their statement every month to avoid interest and other fees, but those that have a non zero balance are distributed by a Gaussian distribution, averaging at around \\$1500 from visual inspection of the graph.
  • Total amount and count change ratio Q4:Q1 is left skewed, and has some outlying values at 3 and 4 respectively, signaling that a few customers converted their spending to this bank's product(s)/credit card(s).

Bivariate EDA - Numerical Columns¶

Let's check the importance of numerical variables.

In [256]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
sns.heatmap(df2.corr(), annot=True, vmin=-1, vmax=1, cmap='Spectral');
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Months on book has a high positive correlation with the customer's age, which makes sense since the older you are, the more likely that you have used a credit card. This also indicates that most customers have been loyal to this company and its product(s).
  • Total transaction amount and count have a slight negative correlation with total relationship count.
  • Avg utilization ratio has a negative correlation with credit limit, indicating that the higher your credit limit, the lower you tend to spend, or perhaps you spend lower in proportion to your credit limit.
  • Avg utilization ratio has a positive correlation with total revolving balance, which is interesting. The higher proporrtion of credit a customer has spent, there is more likelihood of a non zero balance rolling over to the next month AND more chances that the mentioned balance being roller over is higher.
  • Avg utilization ratio has a negative correlation with average open to buy, which is trivial. The more proportion of credit a customer has spent, the less credit they have remaining.

  • More existing customers are in the \$60k-\$80k income bracket, are Male, and have High School or Graduate education level.
  • Overall, all trends seem to be weak - we don't see many strong signals.

Model Evaluation Criterion:¶

Two ways model can make wrong predictions:

  • Predicting that a customer will become attrited when they actually stay (false negative).
  • Predicting that a customer will stay when they actually attrite (false positive).

The second error is more cost-heavy for the bank because the bank's motive is to have a high customer retention. In other words, the bank seeks to identify the customers who will leave their credit card services and why. If the bank wrongly predicts customer attrition, they will lose the customer, and in turn, revenue for the company. Correctly predicting whether an existing customer will attrite will help the bank take possible steps to retain them.

This is a case of maximizing Precision or minimizing false positives.

Let's start by building different models using KFold and cross_val_score and tune the best model using GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV.

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val):
    """
    Check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables - Train set
    tr_pred = model.predict(X_train)

    tr_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    tr_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Recall
    tr_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute Precision
    tr_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_train, tr_pred)  # to compute F1-score
    
    # predicting using the independent variables - Validation set
    val_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    
    val_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(y_val, val_pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    val_recall = metrics.recall_score(y_val, val_pred)  # to compute Recall
    val_precision = metrics.precision_score(y_val, val_pred)  # to compute Precision
    val_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_val, val_pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Train Accuracy": tr_acc, "Train Recall": tr_recall, "Train Precision": tr_precision, "Train F1": tr_f1,\
        "Val Accuracy": val_acc, "Val Recall": val_recall, "Val Precision": val_precision, "Val F1": val_f1},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val):
    """
    Plot confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    tr_y_pred = model.predict(X_train)
    tr_cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_train, tr_y_pred)
    tr_labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / tr_cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in tr_cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    
    ts_y_pred = model.predict(X_val)
    ts_cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_val, ts_y_pred)
    ts_labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / ts_cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in ts_cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,6))
    
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    sns.heatmap(tr_cm, annot=tr_labels, fmt="", ax=axes[0])
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title("Train Set")
    
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    sns.heatmap(ts_cm, annot=ts_labels, fmt="", ax=axes[1])
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title("Validation Set")

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn_test(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = metrics.accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = metrics.recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = metrics.precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = metrics.f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def confusion_matrix_sklearn_test(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

In [306]:
feature_names = X.columns
importances = gbc_best_over.feature_importances_
indices = np.argsort(importances)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
plt.title("Feature Importances")
plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color="violet", align="center")
plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), [feature_names[i] for i in indices])
plt.xlabel("Relative Importance")
plt.show()

Observations:

  • A customer's total transaction count was the most important feature in the Gradient Boosting model, which is intuitively obvious - the more transactions a customer has had in the last 12 months, the more it is indicative that they are liking the product and intend to continue using it.
  • The total transaction amount was the second most important, for similar reasons perhaps - the more amount of money a customer has spent in the last 12 months, the more likely they are to continue doing so with the same product. They may be accruing various incentives such as points, etc on their credit card, which Thera Bank might offer through their products, this incentivizing customers to stay.
  • Total revolving balance, surprisingly, is the third most important feature.
  • Total Relationship count (number of products held by customer) is the fourth most important feature. This is important to note because this is a lever the bank can use for customers predicted to be attrited by the model, so that they can be retained. Similar reasoning can be employed for number of inactive months and contacts count in the last 12 months - Thera Bank can influence these numbers to retain customers who would otherwise attrite.

Pipeline for Productionizing Model¶

We will employ Column Transfer to transform numerical columns separately from categorical columns. Numerical columns had missing null values, which categorical columns might also have in the unseen data. However, categorical columns's missing values will be mode or "most_frequent", whereas numerical columns' missing values will be median (skewed data). Categorical columns will also require onehot encoding/dummy creation.

In [310]:
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps= [
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy='median'))
    ]
)

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps = [
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown = 'ignore'))
    ]
    # handle_unknown = "ignore", allows model to handle any unknown category in the test data
)

# combine both transformers
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers = [
            ("num", numeric_transformer, numerical_cols),
            ("cat", categorical_transformer, categorical_cols),
    ],
    remainder="passthrough",
)
# remainder = "passthrough" has been used, it will allow variables that are present in original data 
# but not in "numerical_columns" and "categorical_columns" to pass through the column transformer without any changes

Business Recommendations¶

  • Customers attrite because largely because they are not using the product enough. Thera Bank can perhaps provide incentives for using their credit card(s) to those customers who have been inactive for more months in the last year, and/or who's spending activity has been decreasing. Some incentives include giving cash back offers, less interest, no late fees, etc.
  • Customers who hold more products are more likely to stay as existing customers. The bank may market other products to those customers who hold only one or two products so they can take advantage of more services offered by the bank, and hence be less likely to attrite.
